SIMPLE: mortuary
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mortuary
<hw>Mor"tu*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Mortuaries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[LL.
<ets>mortuarium</ets>. See <er>Mortuary</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A sort of ecclesiastical heriot, a customary gift
claimed by, and due to, the minister of a parish on the death of a
parishioner. It seems to have been originally a voluntary bequest or
donation, intended to make amends for any failure in the payment of
tithes of which the deceased had been guilty.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A burial place; a place for the dead.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A place for the reception of the dead before burial;
a deadhouse; a morgue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A <er>funeral home</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mortuary</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mortuary
<hw>Mor"tu*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>mortuarius</ets>, fr. <ets>mortuus</ets> dead: cf. F.
<ets>mortuaire</ets>. See <er>Mortal</er>.]</ety> <def>Of or pertaining
to the dead; <as>as, <ex>mortuary</ex> monuments</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mortuary urn</b></col>, <cd>an urn for holding the ashes
of a dead person after cremation.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Morula</ent>⟦br⟧
\'d8
